var definitions = ['<h2>Ich werde dich anrufen, wenn ich zu spät komme.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the auxiliary verb for the future tense in German, "will". It’s used here to indicate a future action.</div><div><strong>dich</strong> This is the second-person singular accusative pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the direct object of the action, the person being called.</div><div><strong>anrufen</strong> This is the main verb of the sentence, meaning "to call". In German, this verb is separable, so the prefix "an-" is detached and appears at the end of the sentence in main clauses.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German, meaning "if" or "when". It introduces the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is repeated here as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>zu spät</strong> This is a phrase meaning "too late". "Zu" means "too" and "spät" means "late".</div><div><strong>komme</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "kommen", meaning "to come". In the subordinate clause, it indicates the condition of the speaker arriving late.</div>','<h2>Wenn wir morgen Zeit haben, werden wir Tennis spielen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is the German word for "if" or "when", and it introduces a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It is the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>morgen</strong> This is the German word for "tomorrow". It indicates the time when the action of the conditional clause might take place.</div><div><strong>Zeit</strong> This is the German noun for "time". In this sentence, it refers to having free time or availability.</div><div><strong>haben,</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It is conjugated to agree with the subject "wir". The comma signifies the end of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is a modal verb in German and means "will" in English. It’s used to form the future tense here, indicating a future event or action. "werden" is the third-person plural form agreeing with the subject "wir".</div><div><strong>wir</strong> Repetition of the first-person plural pronoun "we", serving as the subject of the main clause of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Tennis</strong> This is a German noun meaning "tennis". It is the direct object in the sentence, indicating the sport that will be played.</div><div><strong>spielen.</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "spielen", which means "to play". In this sentence, it is used to describe the action that will be taken if the condition is met. The period at the end of the sentence indicates a full stop.</div>','<h2>Mir würde nicht kalt sein, wenn ich einen Mantel hätte.</h2><div><strong>Mir</strong> This is the dative form of the first-person singular pronoun "ich" in German, equivalent to "to me" in English. It indicates the indirect object or recipient of the action in the sentence.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conjunctive II (Konjunktiv II) form of the auxiliary verb "werden" in the first-person singular. It is used here to form the conditional mood, equivalent to "would" in English.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "not". It negates the statement that follows.</div><div><strong>kalt sein</strong> This is a combination of the adjective "kalt" meaning "cold" and the infinitive form of the verb "sein" meaning "to be". Together they describe the state of feeling cold. In German, the infinitive often goes to the end of the clause or sentence.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if" or "when". It introduces a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative form of the indefinite article "ein" for masculine nouns in German, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>Mantel</strong> This is a masculine noun in German that means "coat". It is the direct object in the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>hätte</strong> This is the conjunctive II (Konjunktiv II) form of "haben", which is "to have" in English, in the first-person singular. It expresses a hypothetical situation or a wish.</div>','<h2>Wenn ich müde wäre, würde ich schlafen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause, which specifies a condition that could trigger the subsequent result.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the conditional clause in this sentence.</div><div><strong>müde</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "tired". In this conditional clause, it describes the state of the subject "ich" (I).</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the first-person singular subjunctive II form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It is used here to describe a hypothetical condition—being tired.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form used in German to express "would" in English. It introduces what would happen were the condition in the first clause met.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Repeated, this is again the first-person singular pronoun in German, here it’s the subject of the result clause in the sentence.</div><div><strong>schlafen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to sleep" in German. Together with "würde", it forms the conditional tense, meaning "would sleep" in English.</div>','<h2>Wenn es draußen wärmer wäre, würden wir ins Wasser gehen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is the German conjunction meaning "if". It is used to introduce a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English and is the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>draußen</strong> This is an adverb meaning "outside" in German.</div><div><strong>wärmer</strong> This is the comparative form of "warm" meaning "warmer" in German, describing the temperature condition required for the action of the main clause to occur.</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the third-person singular subjunctive II form of "sein" (to be). It’s used here for hypothetical or contrary-to-fact conditions.</div><div><strong>würden</strong> This is the plural form of the conditional auxiliary verb "würde", which is used to form the conditional mood. In English, it’s similar to "would".</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English.</div><div><strong>ins Wasser</strong> This is a combination of "in das Wasser", where "in" is a preposition meaning "into", "das" is the definite article "the", and "Wasser" means "water". The phrase means "into the water".</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" in English.</div>','<h2>Ich weiß nicht, ob er ins Kino gehen will.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>weiß</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know". It indicates that the speaker has or does not have knowledge about something.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It negates a statement or clause.</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This is a conjunction in German that means "whether" or "if". It introduces an indirect question or a clause expressing doubt or choice.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>ins</strong> This is a contraction of the German preposition "in" and the definite article "das", which together mean "into the" when referring to masculine or neuter nouns in the accusative case. "Kino" is a neuter noun, so "ins" is the appropriate contraction for saying "into the cinema".</div><div><strong>Kino</strong> This is a neuter noun in German that means "cinema" or "movie theater".</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is an infinitive form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go".</div><div><strong>will</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want". It expresses a desire or intention.</div>','<h2>Wir wissen nicht, ob wir die Zeit haben werden.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "We" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wissen</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know" in English. It describes the action of the subject.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not". It negates the verb or the statement made by the subject.</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This word translates to "whether" or "if" in English. It introduces a dependent clause expressing a condition or a doubt.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> Used again here, this first-person plural pronoun in German, refers back to the subject, "We", within the dependent clause introduced by "ob".</div><div><strong>die Zeit</strong> This phrase consists of the definite article "die" (feminine nominative singular) and the noun "Zeit", which means "time" in English. Together, they translate to "the time".</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. In this sentence, it’s used to indicate possession or existence of the time.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is the future tense auxiliary verb "werden" in German. It’s used here to form the future tense, translating to "will" in English, indicating the action "haben" is occurring in the future.</div>','<h2>Ich frage mich, ob ich ein neues Auto kaufen soll.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>frage</strong> This comes from the verb "fragen", meaning "to ask" in German. It’s the first-person singular present tense form, with "Ich frage" translating to "I ask" in English.</div><div><strong>mich,</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case, which refers back to the subject "Ich" (I). In this context, "mich" is part of the reflexive phrase "ich frage mich", which translates to "I wonder" or "I ask myself".</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "whether" in English. It introduces an indirect question or a clause of doubt.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Again, this is the first-person singular pronoun "I" in English. It’s used here for the second time to refer to the subject of the dependent clause.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It is used in the accusative case here.</div><div><strong>neues</strong> This is an adjective meaning "new" in English. It precedes the noun it modifies and agrees in gender, number, and case with the masculine noun "Auto" and is in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a neuter noun meaning "car" in English. It is in the accusative case as it is the direct object of the verb "kaufen" (to buy).</div><div><strong>kaufen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to buy" in German.</div><div><strong>soll.</strong> This is a modal verb in the first-person singular present tense form, coming from the verb "sollen", which expresses an obligation or suggestion and can be translated as "should" in this context. It modifies the verb "kaufen", forming the phrase "soll kaufen", which means "should buy".</div>','<h2>Kannst du mir sagen, ob das Badezimmer sauber ist?</h2><div><strong>Kannst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "können", which means "to be able to" or "can" in English. It is used here to ask someone if they have the ability to do something.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular dative pronoun in German, equivalent to "me" in English. It indicates that something is being done for or to the speaker.</div><div><strong>sagen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "sagen", which means "to say" or "to tell" in English. In this context, it is used in conjunction with "können" kind of like "can you tell..." in English.</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This is a conjunction in German that can be translated as "whether" or "if" in English. It introduces a dependent clause indicating uncertainty or a question within the sentence.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the neutral definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. Here it precedes and agrees in gender, case, and number with the noun "Badezimmer".</div><div><strong>Badezimmer</strong> This is a neuter noun in German meaning "bathroom".</div><div><strong>sauber</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "clean". It describes the state or condition of the noun "Badezimmer".</div><div><strong>ist?</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It serves as the linking verb connecting the subject "das Badezimmer" to the adjective "sauber", asking about the state of being of the bathroom.</div>','<h2>Sie ist nicht sicher, ob sie ihre Schlüssel hat.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state or condition of the subject.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "not". It is used to negate a statement or indicate the absence of something.</div><div><strong>sicher</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "sure" or "certain". It describes the subject’s state of certainty or confidence.</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This is a German conjunction that introduces a subordinate clause, equivalent to "whether" or "if" in English.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is also the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. However, in this clause, it can also be translated as "her" since it is in the accusative case and is part of a subordinate clause referring to herself in the third person.</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the feminine third-person singular or plural form, equivalent to "her" in English. It shows ownership or possession, indicating that the keys belong to her.</div><div><strong>Schlüssel</strong> This is a German noun meaning "keys". It is in the plural form and is the object of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession and is part of the subordinate clause, detailing what she might or might not possess.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Meine Hunde laufen weg, wenn sie nicht an der Leine sind.</h2><div><strong>Meine</strong> This is the German possessive pronoun in the nominative plural, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates possession, showing that the dogs belong to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Hunde</strong> This is the German word for "dogs" in the nominative plural form. It’s the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>laufen weg</strong> This is a separable verb phrase in German, "laufen" being the infinitive form meaning "to run" and "weg" as a particle meaning "away". Combined as "laufen weg", it means "run away" in the present tense third-person plural to match with "Hunde".</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "when" or "if". It introduces a subordinate clause, indicating a condition.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural personal pronoun in the nominative case, equivalent to "they" in English. In this sentence, it refers to "Hunde" (dogs).</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not", indicating the negation of the following phrase.</div><div><strong>an der Leine</strong> This phrase consists of the preposition "an", the definite article "der" (feminine dative singular), and the noun "Leine" (feminine singular in dative case), which means "leash". Combined, "an der Leine" means "on the leash".</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It serves as the verb for the subordinate clause introduced by "wenn".</div>','<h2>Du würdest dieses Auto kaufen, wenn es funktionieren würde.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the German second-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "you" in English. Here, it is the subject of the conditional sentence.</div><div><strong>würdest</strong> This is the conditional form of the verb "werden" in the second-person singular, which is used to express would or would be in English when forming the conditional mood, usually when talking about hypothetical situations.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German meaning "this". It’s in the accusative case because it is referring to the direct object of the sentence — the car being considered for purchase.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a German noun meaning "car". It’s the direct object of the verb "kaufen" (to buy). Auto is a neuter noun, and here it is in the accusative case due to its position as the direct object.</div><div><strong>kaufen,</strong> This is the verb "to buy" in German, here used in the infinitive form because it follows the modal verb "würdest".</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This German conjunction means "if" or "when". It is introducing a condition that would need to be met for the action in the main clause (buying the car) to take place.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neuter third-person singular pronoun in German, meaning "it". In this sentence, it refers back to the car (Auto).</div><div><strong>funktionieren</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to work" or "to function" in German.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> Again, this is the conditional form of the verb "werden" in the third-person singular. It is used with "funktionieren" to form the conditional mood in the subordinate clause, expressing what condition would lead to buying the car.</div>','<h2>Wenn du Netz hättest, würdest du einen Mechaniker anrufen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is the German conjunction for "if". It introduces a conditional clause, implying that the following condition is hypothetical or contrary to fact.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the hypothetical conditional clause.</div><div><strong>Netz hättest</strong> From the verb "haben" meaning "to have", "hättest" is the second-person singular form in the Konjunktiv II (subjunctive mood used for hypothetical or contrary-to-fact situations) and "Netz" means "network" or "service" in the context of mobile or telephone network. Together, "Netz hättest" expresses "if you had service/network".</div><div><strong>würdest</strong> This is the auxiliary verb "würden" in the second-person singular form, also in Konjunktiv II. It is used to form the conditional mood in German. In English, it corresponds to "would".</div><div><strong>du</strong> Repeated for grammatical structure in German; it is the subject pronoun again, this time in the main clause.</div><div><strong>einen Mechaniker</strong> This is a masculine noun phrase meaning "a mechanic". "Einen" is the accusative article used here because "Mechaniker" is the direct object of the call.</div><div><strong>anrufen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to call". In German, the infinitive often goes to the end of the clause or sentence. In this conditional sentence, it indicates what action would be performed if the condition were met.</div>','<h2>Wenn sie ein Auto hätte, würde sie zu mir nach Hause kommen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause, which specifies a condition that must be met for something else to happen.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This can be the German third-person singular feminine pronoun equivalent to "she" in English or the third-person plural pronoun equivalent to "they" in English. Here it likely refers to "she" as indicated by the singular forms later in the sentence.</div><div><strong>ein Auto</strong> This phrase is composed of the indefinite article "ein" meaning "a" and the noun "Auto", which means "car" in English. Together, they mean "a car".</div><div><strong>hätte</strong> This is the third-person singular past subjunctive form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It’s used here to express a hypothetical situation or condition.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the auxiliary verb "werden", which is used here to form the conditional mood, much like "would" in English. It indicates something that could happen under certain conditions.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> Again, this is the third-person singular feminine pronoun referring to "she" in English. It is the subject of the dependent clause.</div><div><strong>zu mir</strong> This phrase includes the preposition "zu" meaning "to", and "mir", which is the first-person singular dative pronoun meaning "to me". Together, they mean "to me".</div><div><strong>nach Hause</strong> This is a fixed phrase meaning "home" or "to the home". The word "nach" serves as a preposition indicating direction, and "Hause" is an older or formal term for "home".</div><div><strong>kommen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "kommen", which means "to come" in English.</div>','<h2>Wenn er nicht wütend wäre, würde er über den Witz lachen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause, expressing a hypothetical situation.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "not". It negates the adjective that follows it.</div><div><strong>wütend</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "angry". In this sentence, it refers to the state of being of the subject "er".</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the third-person singular subjunctive form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. Here, it is used to indicate a hypothetical or unreal state in the past.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the third-person singular form of the conditional auxiliary "würden", which is used to form the conditional mood in German. It indicates a hypothetical action.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is a repetition of the third-person singular pronoun, again referring to "he" as the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>über</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "about" or "over". It introduces the object of the subject’s potential action.</div><div><strong>den Witz</strong> This translates to "the joke" in English, with "den" being the accusative definite article for masculine nouns, and "Witz" meaning "joke". It is the object of the preposition "über".</div><div><strong>lachen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb meaning "to laugh". In this conditional sentence, it describes the action that "he" would perform if he weren’t angry.</div>','<h2>Wenn die Tür nicht geschlossen wäre, würde ich sie aufmachen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause, indicating what would happen under certain circumstances.</div><div><strong>die Tür</strong> This phrase means "the door" in English. "Die" is the definite article for feminine nouns in the nominative case, and "Tür" is the German word for "door".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not". It is used to negate a verb, adjective, or another adverb.</div><div><strong>geschlossen</strong> This is the past participle of "schließen", which means "to close". In this conditional clause, it is used with "wäre" to form the conditional past tense, meaning "were closed".</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the first or third-person singular subjunctive form of "sein", which means "to be". Here, it is used to express a hypothetical situation; "wäre" means "would be".</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is a conditional auxiliary verb used to form the conditional tense, equivalent to "would" in English. In German, it often precedes an infinitive to form the conditional mood.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the conditional sentence.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person singular feminine pronoun in German, equivalent to "her" or "it" in English. Here it is used as the direct object, referring to "the door".</div><div><strong>aufmachen</strong> This is a separable verb in German that means "to open". As the infinitive form of the verb, it is placed at the end of the clause following the modal verb "würde".</div>','<h2>Wenn es draußen schöner wäre, würden wir in den Park gehen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is the German word for "if". It introduces a conditional clause, indicating a hypothetical situation.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>draußen</strong> This German adverb means "outside". It indicates the location in relation to the hypothetical situation.</div><div><strong>schöner</strong> This is the comparative form of the adjective "schön", which means "beautiful" or "nice" in English. In this context, it’s used to express a hypothetical improvement in weather or outdoor conditions.</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the third-person singular subjunctive II form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It’s used here to describe a hypothetical state or condition in the past.</div><div><strong>würden</strong> This is the plural form of the auxiliary verb "würden", which is used to form the conditional mood in German. It corresponds to "would" in English.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It is the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>in den Park</strong> This phrase combines the preposition "in" (meaning "to" or "into"), the definite article "den" (the masculine accusative form of "the"), and the noun "Park" (meaning "park"), creating the phrase "into the park".</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is the infinite form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" in English. It indicates the action that "we" would take under the hypothetical condition.</div>','<h2>Wenn er nicht so müde wäre, würde er seine Arbeit beenden.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is the German conjunction meaning "if". It’s used to introduce a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It is used to negate a statement or to introduce a negative condition.</div><div><strong>so</strong> This is an adverb meaning "so" or "such" in English. It’s often used for emphasis or to express a degree.</div><div><strong>müde</strong> This is an adjective meaning "tired" in English. It describes the condition of the subject.</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the third-person singular subjunctive II form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It is used here to express a hypothetical or unreal situation.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conjugated form of "würden", a modal verb used to form the conditional mood in German. Here, it means "would".</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is repeated as the subject of the main clause, again referring to "he" in English.</div><div><strong>seine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun meaning "his". It indicates ownership of the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>Arbeit</strong> This means "work" or "job" in English. It’s the object in the sentence that he would finish.</div><div><strong>beenden</strong> This is a verb meaning "to finish" or "to complete". It shows the action that would be taken if the condition were met.</div>','<h2>Wenn die Hosen nicht so groß wären, würde er sie tragen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is the German conjunction for "if". It introduces a conditional clause, specifying a condition for something else to happen.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the definite article for feminine, plural nouns in the nominative case in German, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Hosen</strong> This is the plural form of "Hose", which means "pants" or "trousers" in English. It is a feminine noun in German.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is an adverb meaning "not" in English. It negates the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>so</strong> This is an adverb equivalent to "so" or "such" in English, used here to intensify the adjective "groß".</div><div><strong>groß</strong> This is an adjective meaning "large" or "big" in English. In this sentence, it describes the size of the pants.</div><div><strong>wären</strong> This is the third-person plural subjunctive II form of "sein", which means "to be". Used in a conditional clause, it expresses a hypothetical situation.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional auxiliary verb "würde", which is used to formulate the conditional mood, equivalent to "would" in English.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun "er", which means "he" in English. It is the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun "sie", which means "them" referring back to the pants (Hosen) in English.</div><div><strong>tragen</strong> This is the verb "to wear" or "to carry" in English. In this sentence, it is used in its infinitive form because of the construction with the auxiliary verb "würde".</div>','<h2>Wenn ich meine Hausaufgaben gemacht hätte, würde ich Spaß haben.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction which translates to "if" in English. It’s used to introduce conditional sentences, typically referring to situations that are hypothetical or contrary to fact.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It acts as the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, corresponding to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or relationship to the speaker, referring to the speaker’s "Hausaufgaben" (homework).</div><div><strong>Hausaufgaben</strong> This is the plural noun in German which translates to "homework" in English. It’s the object of the verb "gemacht hätte" in the sentence, referring to the tasks assigned to a student to be completed outside of class.</div><div><strong>gemacht hätte</strong> This verb combination forms the pluperfect subjunctive (past subjunctive) tense of "machen", which means "to do" or "to make" in English. It is used to express a hypothetical condition in the past - something that has not happened. "hätte gemacht" is another correct word order in German.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the verb "werden", which functions here as a helper verb to form the conditional mood, equivalent to "would" in English.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> The pronoun is repeated here as the subject of the result clause of the conditional sentence.</div><div><strong>Spaß haben</strong> This phrase means "to have fun" in English. "Spaß" is the noun "fun", and "haben" is the verb "to have", together they describe the activity that the speaker would be enjoying if the condition had been fulfilled.</div>','<h2>Wenn dein Haar lang wäre, würde der Friseur es schneiden.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause, indicating a hypothesis or a condition.</div><div><strong>dein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the second-person singular in German, meaning "your". It indicates possession or association with the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>Haar</strong> This is a German noun meaning "hair". It’s in the singular form and is neutral gender ("das Haar").</div><div><strong>lang</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "long". It describes the length of the hair in the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is a verb in the subjunctive II past tense form of "sein", which means "to be" in English. The subjunctive mood is used to express hypotheticals, wishes, or conditions contrary to fact.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This word is the conditional form of the verb "werden" in German, used here to form the conditional mood, much like "would" in English.</div><div><strong>der Friseur</strong> This is a German noun meaning "the hairdresser" or "the barber". It’s in the masculine singular form and nominative case, acting as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is a pronoun in German meaning "it". It refers back to "Hair" as the direct object that the hairdresser would cut.</div><div><strong>schneiden</strong> This is a German verb meaning "to cut". In this sentence, it is in the infinitive form because it is being used with "würde" to form the conditional tense.</div>','<h2>Wenn sie nicht durstig wäre, würde sie kein Wasser trinken.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a conjunction in German that means "if". It introduces a conditional clause, which sets the condition for the main clause to happen.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This word can mean either "she" or "they" in German, depending on context. Here, it is used as a third-person singular feminine pronoun, meaning "she".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb meaning "not". It negates the adjective that follows it.</div><div><strong>durstig</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "thirsty".</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the third-person singular subjunctive II form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". The subjunctive mood is used here to express a hypothetical or unreal situation.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the auxiliary verb used to form the conditional mood in German, indicating what would happen under certain circumstances.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> Again, this is the third-person singular pronoun "she". It’s the subject of the subordinate clause created by "würde".</div><div><strong>kein</strong> This is a negation article in German, composed of "kein" meaning "no" or "not any". It negates the noun that follows it.</div><div><strong>Wasser</strong> This is a noun in German that means "water". In this sentence, it is the direct object, indicating what she would not drink.</div><div><strong>trinken</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to drink" in German. It is used here in its base form because it follows the modal verb "würde", forming the conditional tense.</div>','<h2>Wenn er gute Ideen hätte, würde er eine Geschichte schreiben.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>gute</strong> This is the German adjective "gut" in its plural accusative form, meaning "good". It modifies the noun "Ideen".</div><div><strong>Ideen</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Idee", meaning "ideas". It’s the direct object of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>hätte</strong> This is the third-person singular past subjunctive form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it expresses a hypothetical condition.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the verb "werden", used here as a helper verb to form the conditional mood in German.</div><div><strong>er</strong> Repeated again, it’s the third-person singular pronoun "he", indicating the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>eine Geschichte</strong> This phrase consists of the indefinite article "eine", meaning "a", and the noun "Geschichte", meaning "story". Together, they mean "a story" as the direct object of the main clause.</div><div><strong>schreiben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "schreiben", which means "to write". It follows the modal verb "würde" to indicate what "he" would do under the conditional situation.</div>','<h2>Wenn mein Koffer nicht so voll wäre, würde ich ihn schließen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a conjunction in German, which translates to "if" in English. It introduces a condition or hypothetical situation.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is the first-person singular possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates possession, showing that the suitcase (Koffer) belongs to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Koffer</strong> This is a noun in German meaning "suitcase". It is the object being discussed in the sentence.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "not". It negates a statement, in this case, indicating that the suitcase is not as described by the following adjective.</div><div><strong>so</strong> This is an adverb in German that translates to "so" or "such" in English. It intensifies the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>voll</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "full". In this sentence, it describes the state of the "Koffer" (suitcase).</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the subjunctive form of the verb "sein" (to be) in the first-person singular, which translates to "would be" in the context of this sentence. It is used to express hypothetical situations.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the verb "werden" (to become) in the first-person singular. When combined with another verb, in this case "schließen", it forms the conditional mood in German, expressing what the speaker "would" do.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the sentence, referring to the person who would shut the suitcase.</div><div><strong>ihn</strong> This is the third-person singular masculine pronoun in accusative case in German, equivalent to "him" or "it" in English. Here, it refers back to the suitcase, which is masculine ("der Koffer") in German.</div><div><strong>schließen</strong> This is a verb in German meaning "to close". In the sentence, it is used in the infinitive form because it is part of a construction with "würde", which forms the conditional mood.</div>','<h2>Wenn ich mein Teleskop hätte, würde ich die Sterne anschauen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause, which sets the condition for the main clause that follows.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is a possessive adjective in German, meaning "my". It indicates ownership or a relationship to the noun that follows, which in this case is "Teleskop".</div><div><strong>Teleskop</strong> This is a German noun which translates to "telescope" in English. It’s the object being referred to that the speaker would have.</div><div><strong>hätte</strong> This is the first-person singular form of the German verb "haben" in the subjunctive II (Konjunktiv II) tense, which corresponds to "had" in English. It’s used here to express a hypothetical or counterfactual situation. It’s part of the conditional clause linked by "Wenn".</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the German auxiliary verb "werden", used here to form the conditional mood together with the infinitive "anschauen" in the main clause, similar to "would" in English.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Repeated again as the subject of the main clause after the conjunction.</div><div><strong>die Sterne</strong> This is a German noun phrase meaning "the stars". "Die" is the definite article in accusative case for plural nouns, and "Sterne" is the plural form of "Stern", which means "star".</div><div><strong>anschauen</strong> This is the infinitive form of a separable German verb which means "to look at" or "to watch". In the conditional sentence, when used with "würde", it remains in its infinitive form. It’s the action that the speaker would perform if the condition were met.</div>','<h2>Wenn mein Bein nicht gebrochen wäre, würde ich mit euch laufen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is the German word for "if". It is used to introduce a conditional clause, implying that the following statement is a hypothetical or contrary-to-fact situation.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is the German possessive pronoun for "my" in the masculine or neuter form. It indicates ownership or relationship to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Bein</strong> This is the German word for "leg". In this sentence, it is the noun that is possessed by the speaker.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not". It is used here to negate the statement that follows; to indicate that the leg is not in its usual or expected state.</div><div><strong>gebrochen</strong> This is the past participle of the German verb "brechen", which means "to break". Used here, it denotes that the leg is in a broken state.</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the subjunctive form of the German verb "sein", which means "to be". It is used in conditional sentences to express something that is hypothetical or contrary to the reality.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the auxiliary verb "werden" in German. It is used to form the conditional mood, often equating to the English auxiliary "would".</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the dependent clause.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is the German preposition meaning "with". It is used to express accompaniment or participation.</div><div><strong>euch</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English, when addressing more than one person informally.</div><div><strong>laufen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb meaning "to run" or "to walk" (depending on context). In this sentence, it’s expressing the action that the speaker would take if the condition were met.</div>','<h2>Du würdest zittern, wenn das Wasser des Pools kalt wäre.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>würdest</strong> This is the second-person singular form of the conditional mood of the verb "werden", which means "would" in English. It is used to create the conditional tense in German.</div><div><strong>zittern,</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "zittern", which means "to tremble" or "to shiver" in English. In the conditional sentence, it describes the action that "you" would do.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This word translates to "if" or "when" in English. It introduces a condition or hypothetical situation.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is a definite article in German, which means "the" in English. It refers to the noun "Wasser" which follows it.</div><div><strong>Wasser</strong> This is the German noun for "water". It’s neuter gender and singular.</div><div><strong>des Pools</strong> This is a genitive case phrase meaning "of the pool" in English. "des" is the genitive article for masculine and neuter nouns, and "Pool" is the noun for "pool", a masculine noun in German.</div><div><strong>kalt</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "cold". It describes the noun "Wasser".</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the subjunctive or conditional form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. In this sentence, it’s used in the past subjunctive form to indicate a conditional state: "were".</div>','<h2>Wissen Sie, ob es einen Anschluss gibt?</h2><div><strong>Wissen</strong> This is the German verb for "to know" in its infinitive form. Here, it is used in its plural formal imperative form, which roughly translates to "Do you know" in English when addressing someone formally or politely.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal German pronoun for "you". In this sentence, it acts as the subject of the question and corresponds to the formal way of addressing someone either in singular or plural.</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This is a German conjunction that means "if" or "whether". It is used to introduce an indirect question within the sentence.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the German pronoun for "it". In this sentence, it functions as an anticipatory subject, a placeholder for "einen Anschluss" which is the real subject of the embedded clause.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative singular masculine form of the indefinite article "ein", which means "a" or "an" in English. It precedes and agrees with the noun "Anschluss".</div><div><strong>Anschluss</strong> This is a German noun meaning "connection" or "link". It might refer to a transportation connection, like a train or bus connection, or other types of connections. In this accusative case, it’s the direct object of the sentence, the thing about whose existence the speaker is inquiring.</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present form of the German verb "geben", which means "to give". However, in this context, it translates to "there is" or "there are" when used as part of the phrase "es gibt" (there is/are).</div>','<h2>Ich wollte wissen, ob du heute Abend zu mir kommst.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wollte</strong> This is the simple past tense of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want". Here it denotes a past desire or intention.</div><div><strong>wissen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know". In German, an infinitive is often used after a modal verb, as in this case with "wollte".</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This is a conjunction in German that introduces a dependent clause and can be translated as "if" or "whether". It is used to express an indirect question in this sentence.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the dependent clause.</div><div><strong>heute Abend</strong> This is a time expression in German meaning "this evening" or "tonight". "Heute" means "today" and "Abend" means "evening".</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is a preposition in German which has various meanings depending on context. In this sentence, it’s used as part of a direction to a place, equivalent to "to" in English.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the dative case, which means "to me". Here it implies the action of coming is towards the speaker’s location.</div><div><strong>kommst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "kommen", which means "to come". It shows the action performed by the subject "du".</div>','<h2>Können Sie sich erinnern, ob der Räuber ein Mann oder eine Frau war?</h2><div><strong>Können</strong> This is a modal verb in German that means "can" or "to be able to". It is used to express the ability to do something.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used in formal situations or when addressing someone respectfully.</div><div><strong>sich erinnern</strong> This is a reflexive verb phrase meaning "to remember" or "to recall". "Sich" is the reflexive pronoun, and "erinnern" is the verb "to remember".</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This word is a conjunction in German meaning "whether" or "if". It introduces an indirect question or a condition.</div><div><strong>der Räuber</strong> This means "the robber" in German. "Der" is the masculine definite article, and "Räuber" is the noun for a robber or thief.</div><div><strong>ein Mann</strong> This translates to "a man" in English, with "ein" being an indefinite article in its masculine nominative case and "Mann" being the noun for man.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This word is a conjunction in German meaning "or", used to link alternatives.</div><div><strong>eine Frau</strong> This translates to "a woman" in English, where "eine" is the feminine indefinite article in the nominative case and "Frau" is the noun for woman.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the past tense of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state of being in the past.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);